Jun 19 2007 	Great Hotel!	I loved this hotel! Stayed there 6/1-6/3/2007. The staff was very nice and accomodating - room was very big for a New York hotel - bathroom was beautiful, looks like it was recently remodeled. The area was very quaint - coble stones on Stone Street behind the hotel. The free breakfast was fresh, and they had a good selection. The air worked great, and the windows opened also, which was nice for taking a &quot;view from my room&quot; photo. The only issue we had was luke-warm water in the shower, but since it was over 90 degrees outside, it wasn't a big deal - had it been the middle of winter, I might have complained. I would definitely stay at the Wall Street again!	
Jun 13 2007	Delighted.	My first stay in New York and therefore cannot compare this hotel with others but I can say that I would be delighted with this standard anywhere. The buffet breakfast and 'on tap' all day tea/coffee was very welcome and although no other meals are available, the hotel backs onto a small (?historic) street with a number of restaurants. These seemed to be buzzing with the young who work in the financial area. We found the staff pleasant and helpful. We chose this area because it was relatively close to Battery Park. Even at our age (70's) we found it easy to walk there from the hotel. When we preferred to call a taxi, there was always one passing close by. To summarise, we enjoyed our stay in this small hotel and would definitely return.	
Jun 2 2007 	Loved this hotel	This hotel was recommended to me by a friend who lives in NYC while I was on business in the Financial District. Stayed in a roomy, immaculate corner room with a nice view. Make sure you have a map and landmarks to give directions to the cabbies - this is on a small side street that's hard for them to find. However, that also means this is a very quiet, relaxing location - great after the hustle and bustle in the district. The only problem I ran into was an unexpected cold snap in the first week of October. When I complained that turning the room's heater on seemed to do no good, I was advised by hotel staff that the building's heater was not due to be turned on until the middle of October, so the rooms were extremely cold the first day (well, for this Floridian). The weather warmed up the next day, so I didn't have to find out what the hotel's &quot;plan B&quot; would have been.This hotel was far superior to the ones I've stayed at in Midtown, where room rates near $400 to $500 /weekday at a chain/franchise hotel can often get you a &quot;3 star&quot; hotel with 2-star quality. The Wall Street In is off the beaten path yet very convenient. I would definitely stay here again.	
