Dec 8 2006	Out of the Way	The bathroom was newly remodeled, which was very nice. The room and bathroom were very small, and the bed was firm, but comfortable. Many cable channels to entertain us. Very quiet! Very nice lobby. Free internet access with one computer in the lobby. Fitness Center was very small with 2 or 3 machines.However: Our room had a very strong smoke smell, someone had apparently smoked in the room illegally. I wish the hotel had done something about this, but they had not apparently aired out the room at all. The AC was very strong. I was always feeling either too hot or too cold, and the air fanned our faces in bed all night long, which was not very controllable, causing over the course of a week my developing allergic rhinitis and ear irritation. The hotel was in lower Manhattan around which there were few sights/restaurants/shopping, so we had to take the subway everywhere. The nearest subway station was very close, but on the weekend late nights we had to figure out the correct route to get back to the hotel as some routes were closed.	
Nov 7 2006 	Surprisingly elegant!	I recently stayed on a Sunday night at the Wall Street Inn as a first time visitor, as it was located near my early morning destination.It's a bit difficult to find, being wedged on South William street in between the two Wall Street subway stations. A hint to find it is to walk down Beaver Street behind Delmonico's. Either Wall Street subway station is just a couple of blocks away - which gets you quickly to midtown or the theatre district.Reception had my proper reservation, and they were efficient, if a bit gruff and uininvolved at checkin. I was given a room on the third floor with a queen bed - all items in the room appeared either new, or newly upgraded. The design is boutique old world European, with muted floral bedspread and drapes, tasteful artwork, and matching furniture. The room seemed fairly large for Manhattan standards. There was a welcome package of toiletries such as mini toothpaste and lotion - along with an energy bar and vitamin drink mix.The bathroom is lovely, with marble shower, pedestal sink, and items you would expect in 3-4 star hotels, such as lighted mirror, expensive soap/shampoo. Loads of towels were in the room, a nice touch. All was meticulously clean.The rooms have individual heating/cooling systems, which mine seemed to loudly alternate between heat and air conditioning during the night. I got up and turned the system off at some point, as the noise kept me awake. Other than this, there was not much internal noise, but a Sunday night stay may have been the reason. Some outside street noise in the morning, but no more than most Manhattan areas. The queen bed was a bit hard for my liking, but seemed new and not overly uncomfortable.The television seemed new, and worked perfectly. All lights in the room worked, and there seemed to be adequate light, which is a plus. The ironing board and iron are tucked away behind a mirror in the room by the front door. A personal item safe is included in the closet.There's a small room off of the lobby where a continental breakfast is included in the morning. During the day, coffee, tea, and hot chocolate are available. The Wall Street Journal is given in the morning.The hotel has an extensive room service menu that includes local restaurant choices that can be delivered to your room. Spa services are available as well from a nearby exercise studio. The hotel has a workout room, but I did not use it.Just behind the hotel is a street which is roped off as a pedestrian alleyway, and includes a number of bars and restaurants. I visited Adrienne's Pizzapub and was surprised to see a steady stream of patrons on a Sunday night at 5:30. The waiter informed me that more residential units have been built in the Financial District, and that more people are moving there - thus an increased weekend foot traffic flow.Weekend rates are considerably lower than workweek rates, so keep this hotel in mind for weekend trips. One odd item - at checkout, they refused to give me a receipt and insisted my Travelocity receipt would have to suffice. I have never had this issue come up at any other hotel.	
Nov 6 2006 	Great Value More Convenient than expected	We usually stay uptown with our kids because it is close to sites, playgrounds and friends. However, my daughter really wanted to see the Statue of Liberty this time. I found this hotel on the web and called them to ask what was open near them on the weekends since that was my husband's biggest worry. When I was quoted the price of $129 including continental breakfast, I couldn't turn it down!! The rooms were very spacious for NYC and the bathroom was much nicer than our bathroom at home. Our view was off scaffolding, but given the price, I didn't mind. It is an easy walk to the Staten Island Ferry and Battery Park, and even my whiny 4-year-old was able to walk to South Street Seaport and the Brooklyn Bridge - all pleasant walks in the summer. There is a cool fenced-in playground just north of the Seaport that my kids enjoyed.I figured I would use the money I saved on the hotel for cabs, but the hotel is so convenient to subways that we didn't use a cab once. We even walked to the subway with our bags, again - even the 4-year-old. Even with the weekend subway work, we could easily get to both the west and east sides. Also, you are a very short subway ride to some great Brooklyn sites, such as the Botanic Gardens. We didn't go to Brooklyn this time, but plan to the next time we stay at this hotel (and there will be a next time!)There aren't a huge amount of stores and restaurants open on the weekend, but if you look around you can find some. We had a great birthday dinner for my husband at Smorgas, in a cute cobblestone alley right behind the hotel.The continental breakfast is adequate and a blessing when traveling with kids - they just want to eat and get out.If you want to be in the middle of the hubbub of Manhattan, so the club scene, or be close to shopping, this is not the place for you. However, if you want a quiet, reasonably priced, convenient hotel, this place is great.	
Oct 31 2006 	Nothing less than perfect	This is the best NY-deal you can get on the weekend for various reasons: Can you name a beautifully furnished hotel in Manhattan with a four-star-quality that offers stylish rooms for 170 dollars? And as the Wall Street area is quiet on weekends, it's a perfect place for a good sleep. Rooms have all amenities and are cozy. A good continental breakfast is included. Subway is just a block away and Ulysses Bar on the other side of the street is a perfect pub for the late nite drinks. I´d always come back to the Wall Street Inn. Rates explode on Monday till Thursday - but even 270 Dollars would be a good deal in the week - we are talking about Manhattan.	
Oct 28 2006 	Okay for business	I recently stayed at the Wall Street Inn while on a business trip to New York. It is a boutique hotel that has the feel of some of the traditional hotels I have stayed at in London. The hotel is a little difficult to find because it seems to branch off William Street. If you are going there in a cab (understanding that most NYC taxi drivers don't know where they're going), tell the driver it is across the street from Delmonico's. What made it even more difficult at this time is that there is a scaffolding in front of it. You don't go to this hotel for the view. It is a very small hotel that looks out on a narrow street. The first room they gave me was on the second floor looking directly at the scaffolding (it also smelled as if someone had been smoking in it, even though all the rooms are supposed to be non-smoking). So I had them change me to a higher floor so I could have a peek (and I mean, peek - especially since the windows were so dirty) of sunlight. When I got to my room I had various small problems (couldn't get the internet to work, safe wouldn't lock, etc.) but the best thing about this hotel is that every single time I called them I got an immediate and courteous response. If they said they would send someone up right away, they really did. Other than that, the stay was comfortable (although the bed was too soft for my liking), the room was a decent size and the location is accessible by foot to pretty much anything in the Wall Street area, as well as to a subway station. One other good thing is that there is a complimentary continental breakfast, and I found that there was always coffee and some type of pastry or cookie available every time I went into the little breakfast room.	
